<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-857-340  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 857 340.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p104(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PCs for compensation. (Hewlett Associates survey finds increase inemployee compensation automation)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewitt Associates (surveys).andO;Topic:     AutomationPersonnel ManagementSurvey.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The number of companies using computers to determine employee compensationrose dramatically during the last three years, according to a survey byHewitt Associates.andM;The employee-benefit consulting firm surveyed 700 companies and found that 71percent have either partly or fully automated the general recordkeepingprocess for compensation, vs.andP;  only 48 percent in 1986.andP;  Although HewittAssociates did not ask respondents which hardware platforms they used for thecomputerization, a spokesman said that PCs have a significant and growingrole in compensation automation.andM;After general record keeping, the most popular functions to automate (inorder of their popularity) are pay-increase cost analysis, salary-structurecreation, merit-pay calculation, job description and job evaluation.andP;  Thelast two pose particular problems, since fewer than one-third of thecompanies surveyed have automated those aspects of compensation management.andM;One company providing software for compensation management is WMS andamp; Co.andO;Inc., a 12-year-old compensation-management consulting firm.andP;  WMS' offeringis Equi-Comp, a PC-based salary-administration package that integratesjob-evaluation measurement with job pricing and salary planning.andM;To make its calculations, Equi-Comp draws on information downloaded from ahuman-resources database on the corporate mainframe, and on data downloadedfrom WMS' Survey Plus database.andP;  Survey Plus compares job-description andjob-content information from 1,000 companies surveyed by the consulting firm.andM;Many human-resources departments delay performing job-content analysis andsalary-level assessment because the process is laborious when done manually(and is still done manually in more than two-thirds of all departments).andO;Packages such as Equi-Comp allow them to perform these tasks more often,keeping their compensation in line with competing firms.andM;Hewitt Associates, Lincolnshire, Ill.: (312) 295-5000.andP;  WMS andamp; Co.andP;  Inc., Kingof Prussia, Pa.: (215) 783-7733.andO;</TEXT></DOC>